Awesome! Here’s the $BOBI smart contract code tailored for Binance Smart Chain with your exact specs — total supply 1B, 1% burn on every transfer, fixed allocations, and no minting after deployment.

solidity
// SPDX-License-Identifier: MIT
pragma solidity ^0.8.17;

import "@openzeppelin/contracts/token/ERC20/ERC20.sol";
import "@openzeppelin/contracts/access/Ownable.sol";

contract BobiCoin is ERC20, Ownable {
    uint256 public constant MAX_SUPPLY = 1_000_000_000 * 10**18;

    // Burn fee (1%)
    uint256 public burnFeePercent = 1;

    // People Power wallet (can be set once)
    address public peoplePowerWallet;

    // Track if People Power wallet is set
    bool private peoplePowerWalletSet = false;

    constructor(address creatorWallet) ERC20("Bobi Coin", "BOBI") {
        // Mint total supply to contract initially
        _mint(address(this), MAX_SUPPLY);

        // Allocate 100M to creator wallet (you)
        uint256 creatorAmount = 100_000_000 * 10**18;
        _transfer(address(this), creatorWallet, creatorAmount);

        // Allocate 300M to People Power wallet later (will call setPeoplePowerWallet)
        // 600M remain locked in contract for now (public sale + ecosystem + dev etc.)
    }

    // Owner can set the People Power wallet once
    function setPeoplePowerWallet(address _wallet) external onlyOwner {
        require(!peoplePowerWalletSet, "People Power wallet already set");
        require(_wallet != address(0), "Invalid wallet address");
        peoplePowerWallet = _wallet;

        // Transfer 300M tokens to People Power wallet
        uint256 amount = 300_000_000 * 10**18;
        _transfer(address(this), peoplePowerWallet, amount);

        peoplePowerWalletSet = true;
    }

    // Override transfer to implement 1% burn
    function _transfer(
        address sender,
        address recipient,
        uint256 amount
    ) internal override {
        uint256 burnAmount = (amount * burnFeePercent) / 100;
        uint256 sendAmount = amount - burnAmount;

        super._transfer(sender, address(0), burnAmount); // Burn tokens
        super._transfer(sender, recipient, sendAmount);
    }

    // Disable minting
    function _mint(address account, uint256 amount) internal override {
        require(totalSupply() + amount <= MAX_SUPPLY, "Max supply exceeded");
        super._mint(account, amount);
    }
}

🔍 Most Common Reasons:

  1. The constructor() didn't assign the initial supply
    This is the #1 cause. If the constructor didn’t include a line like:

    solidity
    balances[msg.sender] = totalSupply;

    then no wallet was assigned the tokens — they just exist, unallocated.

  2. The initial supply was set but not transferred to your wallet
    If the tokens were minted but assigned to address(0) or another wallet accidentally, they’ll be lost or stuck.

  3. The decimals or supply were misconfigured
    If you wanted 1,000,000,000 tokens but only set 1000000, you might have a mismatch in what you expect.

  4. TRON IDE (TronBox / TronStudio) compiler glitch or wrong field input
    A wrong "Origin Energy Limit" or interaction parameter may cause a contract to deploy without executing your constructor.

✅ Let’s Check Now:

Please do the following:

solidity
balanceOf("TGaCiDM3Ym6mHwzcKBBsci1adyK9fzaymq")
